        .span10
          .row-fluid
            h1 Other Transformers
          +transformer('cdata')
            .row-fluid
              p cdata just wraps code in <code>cdata</code> tags.  You don't need to install anything to use cdata
            +displayTransform('cdata')(post='xml').
              foo bar
          +transformer('coffee-script')
            .row-fluid
              p coffee-script is a high level language that compiles to JavaScript.  To use it you will need to install coffee-script:
              +code(false).
                $ npm install coffee-script
            +displayTransform('coffee-script')(pre='coffeescript', post='javascript').
              # Assignment:
              number   = 42
              opposite = true

              # Conditions:
              number = -42 if opposite

              # Functions:
              square = (x) -> x * x

              # Arrays:
              list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

              # Objects:
              math =
                root:   Math.sqrt
                square: square
                cube:   (x) -> x * square x
          +transformer('cson')
            .row-fluid
              p coffee-script is like JSON but with coffee-script like syntax.  To use it you will need to install cson:
              +code(false).
                $ npm install cson
            +displayTransform('cson')(pre='coffeescript', post='javascript').
              {
                abc: [
                  'a'
                  'b'
                  'c'
                ]
                a:
                  b: 'c'
              }
          +transformer('markdown')
            .row-fluid
              p markdown is a system for writing documents.  The aim is that markdown should be easy to read even when it's in plain text form, but that it can also compile to a nicer formatted html view:
            +displayTransform('markdown')(pre='markdown', post='xml').
              # Heading 1
              ## Heading 2

              ```
              A code sample
              ```

               - ItemA
               - ItemB
               - ItemC

               1. One
               2. Two
               3. Three
          +transformer('html2jade')
            .row-fluid
              p html2jade attempts to convert html back into jade.  Jade is a templating language.  To use html to jade you will need to install it at version 0.0.7:
            +code(false).
              $ npm install html2jade@0.0.7
            +displayTransform('html2jade')(pre='xml', post='jade').
              <!doctype html>
              <html>
                  <head>
                    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/site.css" />
                    <title>Hello</title>
                  </head>
                  <body>
                    <h1>Hello world!</h1>
                  </body>
              </html>
          +transformer('component')
            .row-fulid
              :markdown
                The two transformers 'component-js' and 'component-css' produce the JavaScript and CSS files from a [component](https://github.com/component/component).  This can't be easilly demoed here because it requires multiple files to make sense.  To use, first install component-builder.

              +code(false)
                $ npm install component-builder

              :markdown
                Then you can build like any other transformer by pointing it at the `component.json` file.